Dallas Housing Market Study

Maxwell Fritz

11/18/2019

Overview

This project looks to analyze residential housing values in Dallas County as determined by the Dallas County Appraisal District (DCAD) for FY2019 for factors that would define clusters of individuals, labelled primarily by their requests for appraisal exemptions.

Other trends within appraisal values will be generally analyzed, particularly in determining factors that influence appraisal values, and whether variable importance differs in models built partitioned at the city level and ostensibly, at the neighborhood parcel level.


































Data


The majority of the original data will be sourced from data products provided publicly by the DCAD (http://www.dallascad.org/DataProducts.aspx), including individual parcel and GIS labelling information for all residential housing in the county as well as appraisal exemption requests for the 2018-2019 appraisal year. In addition, data from Zillow will be matched against home and neighborhood parcel data to calculate year over year market value change.

Additional data will be sourced from various public entities as required, particularly GIS data to augment analysis of neighborhood parcels. Synthesized data includes variables appended to the appraisal data sets to flag desired data and to create labels for final model building, as well as some generated to condense and unify unwieldy features.

The data is stored in a public MySQL instance at the following endpoint: instance-dcad.cv8hacktx1ql.us-east-1.rds.amazonaws.com. The initial dataset is composed of nine (9) tables that generally demarcate parcels and appraisal information by account identifier in 80+ features of varying scope, type, and completeness. Data for some 830,000 accounts is included as well as 2019 appraisal exemptions that number approximately 600,000.


































Variables

After joining tables, cleaning data, etc., the following variables are left over and utilized in the following models. Note that any variables containing lowercase characters are calculated fields.

Variable Type Meaning
TOT_VAL Integer Total appraised value (2019)
PREV_MKT_VAL Integer Market value previous year
delta Integer Change in appraised value
PROPERTY_CITY Factor City of appraised property
ACT_AGE Integer Age of property (years)
TOT_MAIN_SF Integer Square footage of home
NUM_STORIES_DESC Factor Number of stories
NUM_FIREPLACES Integer Number of fireplaces
NUM_BEDROOMS Integer Number of bedrooms
NUM_FULL_BATHS Integer Number of full baths
NUM_HALF_BATHS Integer Number of half baths
NUM_KITCHENS Integer Number of kitchens
POOL_IND Binary Indicator for pool
appraisal Binary Appraisal exemption approved?
is_HP Binary Is the home in Highland Park?

Stepwise selection

Perform stepwise selection of variables.

# exhaustive
lm.regfit.full=regsubsets(TOT_VAL ~ PROPERTY_CITY + AREA_SIZE + ACT_AGE + TOT_MAIN_SF + NUM_STORIES_DESC + NUM_FIREPLACES + NUM_BEDROOMS + NUM_FULL_BATHS + NUM_HALF_BATHS + NUM_KITCHENS + POOL_IND, data=lm.train.price,nvmax=15)

# forward
lm.regfit.fwd=regsubsets(TOT_VAL ~ PROPERTY_CITY + AREA_SIZE + ACT_AGE + TOT_MAIN_SF + NUM_STORIES_DESC + NUM_FIREPLACES + NUM_BEDROOMS + NUM_FULL_BATHS + NUM_HALF_BATHS + NUM_KITCHENS + POOL_IND, data=lm.train.price,nvmax=15,method="forward")

# backward
summary(regfit.fwd)
lm.regfit.bwd=regsubsets(TOT_VAL ~ PROPERTY_CITY + AREA_SIZE + ACT_AGE + TOT_MAIN_SF + NUM_STORIES_DESC + NUM_FIREPLACES + NUM_BEDROOMS + NUM_FULL_BATHS + NUM_HALF_BATHS + NUM_KITCHENS + POOL_IND, data=lm.train.price,nvmax=15,method="backward"

































































































KNN (Highland Park)

Build dataset

set.seed(6323)

# target variable is factor
knn.dataset$PROPERTY_CITY <- factor(knn.dataset$PROPERTY_CITY)

# Highland Park Zip Code
knn.dataset_PLOT_HP <- knn.dataset %>%
  filter(str_detect(PROPERTY_ZIPCODE, "^75225"))%>% # some records include full zip
  filter(!is.na("TOT_VAL"))%>%
  mutate(isHP = TRUE)

# Not Highland Park (does it matter where?)
knn.dataset_PLOT <- knn.dataset %>%
  filter(str_detect(PROPERTY_ZIPCODE, "^75210") | str_detect(PROPERTY_ZIPCODE, "75215"))%>%
  filter(!is.na("TOT_VAL"))%>%
  mutate(isHP = FALSE) %>%
  rbind(knn.dataset_PLOT_HP)

# Create training and testing data sets
idx = sample(1:nrow(knn.dataset_PLOT), size = 600)
train.idx = 1:nrow(knn.dataset_PLOT) %in% idx
test.idx =  ! 1:nrow(knn.dataset_PLOT) %in% idx

knnPLOTtrain = knn.dataset_PLOT[train.idx, c(knn.features,"isHP")]
knnPLOTtest = knn.dataset_PLOT[test.idx, c(knn.features,"isHP")]

# Get labels
knnPLOTlabels = knn.dataset_PLOT[train.idx, "isHP"]
































Models

# Do knn for three values of k
knnPLOTfit1 = knn(knnPLOTtrain, knnPLOTtest, knnPLOTlabels, k=1)
knnPLOTfit3 = knn(knnPLOTtrain, knnPLOTtest, knnPLOTlabels, k=3)
knnPLOTfit10 = knn(knnPLOTtrain, knnPLOTtest, knnPLOTlabels, k=10)
































Results

# Create a dataframe to simplify charting
knnPLOT.df1 = data.frame(knnPLOTtest, predicted = knnPLOTfit1)
knnPLOT.df3 = data.frame(knnPLOTtest, predicted = knnPLOTfit3)
knnPLOT.df10 = data.frame(knnPLOTtest, predicted = knnPLOTfit10)

# First use Convex hull to determine boundary points of each cluster
knnPLOT.df1h = data.frame(x = knnPLOT.df1$TOT_MAIN_SF, 
                      y = knnPLOT.df1$TOT_VAL/1000, 
                      predicted = knnPLOT.df1$predicted)
knnPLOT.df3h = data.frame(x = knnPLOT.df3$TOT_MAIN_SF, 
                      y = knnPLOT.df3$TOT_VAL/1000, 
                      predicted = knnPLOT.df3$predicted)
knnPLOT.df10h = data.frame(x = knnPLOT.df10$TOT_MAIN_SF, 
                      y = knnPLOT.df10$TOT_VAL/1000, 
                      predicted = knnPLOT.df10$predicted)

find_hull1 = function(df) df[chull(df$x, df$y), ]
boundary1 = ddply(knnPLOT.df1h, .variables = "predicted", .fun = find_hull1)
find_hull3 = function(df) df[chull(df$x, df$y), ]
boundary3 = ddply(knnPLOT.df3h, .variables = "predicted", .fun = find_hull3)
find_hull10 = function(df) df[chull(df$x, df$y), ]
boundary10 = ddply(knnPLOT.df10h, .variables = "predicted", .fun = find_hull10)

# Confusion matrix for each k
knncf1<-confusionMatrix(data=knnPLOT.df1$predicted, as.factor(knnPLOT.df1$isHP), positive = 'TRUE')
knncf3<-confusionMatrix(data=knnPLOT.df3$predicted, as.factor(knnPLOT.df3$isHP), positive = 'TRUE')
knncf10<-confusionMatrix(data=knnPLOT.df10$predicted, as.factor(knnPLOT.df10$isHP), positive = 'TRUE')

# Pull out accuracy
knncf1_acc<-knncf1$overall["Accuracy"]
knncf3_acc<-knncf3$overall["Accuracy"]
knncf10_acc<-knncf10$overall["Accuracy"]

# Plot
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
ggplot(knnPLOT.df1, aes(TOT_MAIN_SF, TOT_VAL/1000, color = predicted, fill = predicted)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3, pch=20) +

  ylab("Total Value (thousands of USD)")+

  theme_bw()
ggplot(knnPLOT.df3, aes(TOT_MAIN_SF, TOT_VAL/1000, color = predicted, fill = predicted)) +

Appraisal Models

Building dataset

set.seed(6323)

appraisal.all <- price_data %>%
  na.omit()%>%
  mutate(appraisal = ifelse(ACCOUNT_NUM %in% exemptions_granted$ACCOUNT_NUM,'TRUE','FALSE'))
appraisal.all<-appraisal.all[(c("TOT_VAL",'PREV_MKT_VAL','delta','PROPERTY_CITY','ACT_AGE','TOT_MAIN_SF','NUM_STORIES_DESC','NUM_FIREPLACES','NUM_BEDROOMS','NUM_FULL_BATHS','NUM_HALF_BATHS','POOL_IND','NUM_KITCHENS','appraisal'))]

Data is highly skewed towards the False case; try oversampling

# Divide data by case
appraisal.all.true <- appraisal.all %>% filter(appraisal=='TRUE')
appraisal.all.false <- appraisal.all %>% filter(appraisal=='FALSE')

# Oversample the true case
appraisal.true.oversampled.set <- sample(1:nrow(appraisal.all.true), 20000, replace = TRUE)

# Match oversampled true with original false set
appraisal.true.oversampled <- appraisal.all.true[appraisal.true.oversampled.set,]
appraisal.all.oversampled <- bind_rows(appraisal.all.false,appraisal.true.oversampled) #105695 obs

# Sample for test and training from new data set
set.seed(6323)

appraisal.train.set <- sample(1:105695, 84000, replace = FALSE)
appraisal.train<-appraisal.all.oversampled[appraisal.train.set,]  
appraisal.test<-appraisal.all.oversampled[-appraisal.train.set,]

Discussion

Generally speaking, all of the appraisal models built have very high accuracy. However, given our dataset is still so strongly skewed (1:5 | True:False), our default rate by assigned all observations to the majority class is 80%, which means that our LDA and Logistic models performed significantly worse than previously thought.



In addition, it is clear in certain models that our oversampling has damaged the integrity of the model, even though it may reduce the domination of the majority class in predictions.



This would show up specificallyin our KNN models with resampled points existing in both the training and test data set essentially giving free answers to our model. In addition, a QDA classifier was unable to run given the type and scale of resampling technique implemented.



Given this, the Random Forest model currently provides the most accurate model when factoring in generalizability.




Overall, the data provided proved more difficult to work with than expected, which had significant effects on my ability to build accurate models. Some difficulties included:

  • many data points were incorrectly coded,
  • many were NA or placeholder values, and
  • a majority of the data proved to be rollover observations, i.e.appraisals that are renewed automatically by the DCAD.
































Next Steps

Next steps include:

  • implement different(synthetic) oversampling techniques
  • try undersampling the majority class
  • complete model tuning
